## Location
src/vdd/parsing.rs:27-94
## Violation
extract_json_from_response has four sequential blocks that each search for a delimiter, slice via str::get, and re-test inner content. The pattern repeats:

```rust
if let Some(start) = text.find("```json") {
    let json_start = start + "```json".len();
    if let Some(rest) = text.get(json_start..) {
        if let Some(end) = rest.find("```") {
            if let Some(inner) = rest.get(..end) {
                return Some(inner.trim().to_string());
            }
        }
    }
}

if let Some(start) = text.find("```") {
    let json_start = start + 3;
    if let Some(after_fence) = text.get(json_start..) {
        ...
    }
}
```

Each block does the same thing — find a delimiter, descend, slice, return. Bugs in one block will be missed when reviewing the next because the structure looks identical at a glance. A future change to handle a new fence pattern (e.g., ~~~json) means writing yet another nearly-identical block.

## Mandated refactor
Extract a helper:

```rust
fn extract_between(text: &str, open: &str, close: &str) -> Option<String> {
    let start = text.find(open)? + open.len();
    let rest = text.get(start..)?;
    let end = rest.find(close)?;
    rest.get(..end).map(|s| s.trim().to_string())
}

pub(crate) fn extract_json_from_response(text: &str) -> Option<String> {
    extract_between(text, "```json", "```")
        .or_else(|| extract_after_fence_skip_lang(text))
        .or_else(|| extract_balanced_braces_after(text, r#"{"findings""#))
        .or_else(|| extract_first_to_last_brace(text))
}
```

Each helper has one responsibility and is independently testable. The fallback chain shows the strategy explicitly.

